How to Finance the Green Transition
New York – This week, world leaders gathered in New York at the United Nations to assess the global war on climate change and submit new climate-mitigation pledges.
The climate crisis is serious, and our actions are not fast enough.
We are lagging behind in shifting to high gear.
Accelerating the pace of change requires joint efforts from both public and private sectors.
#1 <s>Luckily, thanks to the work of the Climate Finance Leadership Initiative (CFLI), there is growing private sector collaboration to combat climate change.
#2 <s>Under the leadership of UN Climate Action Special Envoy Michael Bloomberg, the CFLI was established with the aim of mobilizing global private capital to address this critical issue.
#3 <s>This month, the CFLI released a new report, Financing the Low Carbon Future, which outlines how to expand green finance to support a orderly low-carbon economic transition and highlights opportunities for public-private cooperation to achieve the Paris Climate Agreement goals from 2015.
#4 <s>The European Investment Bank (EIB) is the largest multilateral investor in climate-related projects worldwide.
#5 <s>But now, responding to calls from European heads of state and the newly elected President of the European Commission Ursula von der Leyen, we are gearing up to step up the EIB's role as a specialized climate bank for the EU.
EIB will mainstream climate considerations, focusing on low-carbon investments, and over the next decade commit at least one trillion euros to low-carbon projects.
To achieve this, at least 50% of EIB financing will be directed toward climate action and environmental sustainability by 2025.
By the end of 2020, we will align all our financing activities with the objectives of the Paris Climate Agreement.
As an important first step, we will phase out energy projects dependent on fossil fuels.
In addition, we will position the EIB as a green finance incubator, dedicated to mobilizing other resources to help economies transition to a low-carbon future.
As an EU bank, our mission is to invest in Europe's future, and the most pressing issue is undoubtedly climate change.
The climate crisis is acute, and our resolve is strong.
This summer, Europe suffered record heatwaves and crop failures due to last year's drought.
Many developing countries have had similar experiences.
Floods and other climate-induced phenomena are costing major cities billions of dollars annually, and many more lives are at risk.
But the climate crisis is also an opportunity, as funding for new green infrastructure can create jobs, stimulate economic growth, and reduce air pollution plaguing major cities around the world.
Shifting investment models can accelerate the move away from fossil fuels. This shift has already begun.
Market forces are increasingly favoring clean energy over fossil fuels.
In 2011, nearly half of the US coal-fired power plants were retired, while the clean energy industry created 3.3 million jobs, compared to fewer than 100,000 in the coal industry.
Furthermore, more and more American cities and states are committed to achieving net-zero emissions by 2050.
They will receive support from Beyond Carbon, a initiative launched by Bloomberg Philanthropies last year to support full decarbonization of the US economy.
As an international community, we must not only invest in clean energy but also reduce investment in dirty energy.
Currently, in terms of fossil fuel subsidies, we are effectively spending money to promote climate change and air pollution.
These public funds should be directed towards technologies that drive the green transition, such as electric vehicles.
These investments will yield immense returns, including reducing the enormous costs of air pollution on public health.
Furthermore, there are numerous measures we can take to channel the necessary funding.
#2 <s>First, we must improve data and disclosure standards.
For too long, businesses and investors have been in the dark about climate-related risks, unsure of the rationale for reducing carbon emissions or protecting assets from extreme weather impacts.
This is starting to change.
The recommendations from the Task Force on Climate-related Financial Disclosures are guiding companies to allocate capital in a more sustainable way and enabling investors to reward those that are taking climate change seriously.
Second, we must clarify investment risks related to green finance.
Cities account for over 70% of carbon emissions, but only a few developing world cities have access to credit ratings.
The result is that the total investment in clean buses, energy-efficient buildings, and other emission-reduction projects has been affected.
Governments and listed banks must step up to help cities attract capital for these projects, including through initiatives like the Global Covenant of Mayors for Climate & Energy, which is supported by the EIB and co-led by Bloomberg Philanthropies.
Third, we need to modernize our grids.
Refunds and tax incentives have promoted the expansion of wind and solar power, reducing costs for both businesses and consumers.
Now, we should introduce similar programs to accelerate the deployment of battery storage and other emerging technologies, overcoming intermittency issues more quickly.
In addition, better grid connectivity can enable regions with excess wind and solar power to supply areas with shortages.
Governments can play a leading role in both areas, encouraging more private investment in clean power.
Finally, we must continue to expand the market for green investments.
2007, the EIB issued the world's first green bond on the Luxembourg Stock Exchange, and since then, the green bond market has expanded to $136 billion.
But compared to a global bond market worth $100 trillion, this is just a drop in the bucket.
Therefore, the EIB is helping to develop sustainable finance standards for the EU so that investors can compare green projects as they would with standard bonds.
Better and more information about the carbon footprint of investments could enable informed decisions by investors, driving more private capital into low-carbon projects.
This is how we finance the green transition.
